is located on two sites on the [[Isle of Portland]] in the [[English county]] of [[Dorset]].\n\n==History==\nThe Isle of Portland Aldridge Community Academy was formed in September 2012 from the merger of Brackenbury Infant School, Grove Infant School, Southwell County Primary School, Underhill Community Junior School and Royal Manor Arts College. As an academy, the school was originally sponsored by [[Aldridge Foundation|The Aldridge Foundation]] and [[Dorset County Council]].<ref name=\"gias-old\">{{cite web |title=Isle of Portland Aldridge Community Academy - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Establishments/Establishment/Details/138388 |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nA new campus, Osprey Quay Campus, opened in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dorsetecho.co.uk/news/11338362.fond-farewell-for-historic-school-building/|title=Fond farewell for historic school building|website=Dorset Echo}}</ref> It was followed by the opening of the main campus site, Maritime House, in September 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title = New Principal Visits Maritime House {{!}} Isle of Portland Aldridge Community Academy|url = http://www.ipaca.uk.com/8869/new-principal-visits-maritime-house/|website = www.ipaca.uk.com|accessdate = 2015-10-27}}</ref> In September 2016, Aldridge Education multi-academy trust took over the responsibility for all Aldridge Schools from the Aldridge Foundation. In October it was announced that the Academy would not be joining the multi-academy trust and that Aldridge were standing down as sponsor. Dorset County Council remains a sponsor. \n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://aldridgeeducation.org/news/statement-ipaca/|title=Statement On IPACA|website=Aldridge Education}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2016, the school was inspected by Ofsted and declared inadequate.<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2016\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2016 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/2638907 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> IPACA became Atlantic Academy Portland in September 2017, managed by [[Aspirations Academies Trust]].<ref name=\"TES\">{{cite web |title=Atlantic Academy Portland - Tes Jobs |url=https://www.tes.com/jobs/employer/atlantic-academy-portland-1083353 |website=www.tes.com |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Academics==\nAspirations Academies Trust is a [[multi-academy trust]] supporting 16 academies in [[Dorset]], [[Banbury]] and [[Feltham]] in West London.<ref name=\"gias-trust\">{{cite web |title=Aspirations Academies Trust - GOV.UK |url=https://get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/Groups/Group/Details/2187#details |website=get-information-schools.service.gov.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The school they inherited was 'inadequate';<ref name=\"Ofsted Report 2016\">{{cite web |title=Ofsted Report 2016 |url=https://files.ofsted.gov.uk/v1/file/2638907 |website=ofsted.gov.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> they aimed to create an academy where the students believed in themselves and were actively engaged in their own learning andd saw a connection between the learning tasks and their ambitions for the future. They needed to create a challenging curriculum and disruption free learning. It is an \u2018all through\u2019 Academy, with all years housed within the same school building. <ref name=TES/> \n\nAn early change was to reduce the schools capacity, the [[pupil admission number|PAN]] or school number in jargon, from 1580 to 1220, to have year groups of 60 in Primary and 120 in Secondary, where previously it was 60 and 150.  This reduces overcrowding while allowing all pupils to be on a single site.<ref name=\"PAN\">{{cite web |title=Consultation on the proposal to change the Published Admission Number for the primary and secondary provision at Atlantic Academy Portland |url=http://www.portlandtowncouncil.gov.uk/Agenda-Nov-2017.pdf |website=/www.portlandtowncouncil.gov.uk |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n===Curriculum===\nAs an all-through school, with youngsters from reception class to upper sixth- there needs to be a unified teaching approach in all key stages, from [[Key Stage 1|Key Stage R]] to [[Key Stage 5]]. The Aspirations Academies Trust is developing a common curricular approach the will be used in each of its academies, albeit reflecting the local community and the particular needs of its students, <ref name=\"No Limits\">{{cite web |title=Aspirations No Limits Curriculum - Atlantic Academy Isle of Portland |url=http://www.atlantic-aspirations.org/2466/aspirations-no-limits-curriculum |website=www.atlantic-aspirations.org |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> It will contain :\n*The [[Early Years Foundation Stage|Early Years]] curriculum requirements,\n*The [[National Curriculum]] in Key Stages 1, 2, 3 and 4.\n*\u2018No Limits: Education for success in the 21st century\u2019-a trust wide [[KS2]] and [[KS3]] teaching scheme\n*The [[EBacc]] academic programme at [[KS4]]\n*The trust [[CEIL]] programme at [[KS5|Post 16]]<ref name=\"No Limits\"/>\n===Current subjects===\nLearning in Key Stage Two is linked to a central topic, such as a Energy and Sustainability or \u2018The Middle East\u2019.  The topic mapping has been specially designed to support the needs of the pupils.<ref name=\"KS2\">{{cite web |title=Key Stage Two Curriculum - Atlantic Academy Isle of Portland |url=http://www.atlantic-aspirations.org/713/key-stage-two-curriculum |website=www.atlantic-aspirations.org |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref> \n \nAt Key Stage 3, year 8 and 9 students study English, Maths, Science,  French, Music, Art, Drama, RE, Geography, History, Design Technology ; Computer Science and Business Enterprise and PE. In Year 7 the students study the new No Limits Curriculum: which will include English, Maths, Science,  French, Music, Art, Drama, Geography, History, Design Technology and PE.<ref name=\"KS3\">{{cite web |title=Key Stage Three Curriculum - Atlantic Academy Isle of Portland |url=http://www.atlantic-aspirations.org/714/key-stage-three-curriculum |website=www.atlantic-aspirations.org |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nAt Key Stage 4 students study a mixture of [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSEs]] and [[Business and Technology Education Council|BTECs]]. All pupils study English, English Literature, Maths, and Science. They are allowed four options, two of which must be [[EBacc]] subjects, and two chosen from Art, business Studies, Drama, Music, Food, Product Design and Philosophy. The Ebacc subjects are History, Geography, French and Computer Science.<ref name=\"KS4\">{{cite web |title=Key Stage Four Curriculum - Atlantic Academy Isle of Portland |url=http://www.atlantic-aspirations.org/715/key-stage-four-curriculum |website=www.atlantic-aspirations.org |accessdate=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Schools in Dorset}}\n\n[[Category:Primary schools in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Secondary schools in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Academies in Dorset]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2012]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:KS2\u2192Key Stage 2,KS4\u2192Key Stage 4,KS5\u2192Key Stage 5", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atlantic_Academy_Portland"}
